<figureCitation id="C5FF10EEFF82EF41FF12F838FEAEF810" box="[151,283,1933,1960]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1719,1743]" captionTargetBox="[153,1431,564,1688]" captionTargetId="figure-128@42.[151,1437,560,1695]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 20. Species of Pycnopalpini and Scaphurae (Phaneropterinae) from the ParNa Iguaçu. A and B: Pycnopalpa bicordata, male and female; C and D: Topana cincticornis, male and female; E and F: Scaphura elegans, male and female; G and H: S. nigra, male and female; I: Scaphura sp. 1, female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550105" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550105/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Fig. 20C, D</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FF82EF41FF12F860FE54F857" box="[151,481,2005,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF82EF41FF12F860FE54F857" blockId="42.[151,481,2005,2031]" box="[151,481,2005,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF82EF41FF12F860FE86F857" bold="true" box="[151,307,2005,2031]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Distribution:</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="25D34CFBFF82EF41FEBFF860FE36F857" box="[314,387,2005,2031]" name="Brazil" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion id="9F00C289FF82EF41FE08F860FE68F857" box="[397,477,2005,2031]" country="Brazil" name="Parana" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Paraná</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="15DE5FE0FF83EF40FF42FF23FBDFFCAC" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FF23FBF3FEA4" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FF23FEE7FF08" bold="true" box="[199,338,150,176]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Comments:</emphasis>
This is the first record of females of this species. The tegmina of females are oval, larger than the tegmina of males, and entire green, without stains. The ovipositor is curved upwards, a little longer than the pronotum and as high as the abdomen, with ventral valves curved along all its extension, with apex without reaching the apex of the dorsal valves, a condition also found in another species of 
<taxonomicName id="9AC477E8FF83EF40FC2FFEB7FBF7FEA4" authority="Fianco &amp; Szinwelski &amp; Faria, 2022" authorityName="Fianco &amp; Szinwelski &amp; Faria" authorityYear="2022" box="[938,1090,258,284]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" status="trib. n." tribe="Pycnopalpini">Pycnopalpini</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FE93FE0CFE30" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FE93FEEEFEF8" bold="true" box="[199,347,294,320]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Bioacoustics</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="C5FF10EEFF83EF40FEEFFE93FE4DFEF9" box="[362,504,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 21" captionStartId="44.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[211,1377,185,1908]" captionTargetId="figure-29@44.[203,1385,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="44" captionText="FIGURE 21. Calling songs of Phaneropterini and Scaphurae (Phaneropterinae) from the ParNa Iguaçu. A–C: Viadana (Viadana) piracicabae; D–F: Topana cincticornis; G–I: Scaphura elegans. A, D and G: sonogram of one echeme sequence; B, E and H: sonogram of two syllables; C, F and I: respective spectrograms." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6550109" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6550109/files/figure.png" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Fig. 21 D–F</figureCitation>
): Males stridulate only at night, producing a sequence of echemes during about one second, in crescendo. Each sequence is composed by four to seven echemes, each of them composed by two syllables of similar intensity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FE26FDDCFE14" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,617,402,429]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FE26FE1EFE14" box="[199,427,402,428]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Dominant frequency</emphasis>
: 31.4 ± 1.5 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FE03FE45FE68" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,496,438,465]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FE03FEF5FE68" box="[199,320,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Bandwidth</emphasis>
: 5.0 ± 3.0 kHz.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FE6EFC8BFE4D" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,830,474,501]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FE6EFE82FE4C" box="[199,311,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Duration:</emphasis>
Syllable: 7.0 ± 3.0 ms; Echeme: 560 ± 98 ms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF42FE4AFDE8FDA1" blockId="43.[151,1437,150,537]" box="[199,605,510,537]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF42FE4AFEEAFDA0" box="[199,351,510,536]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Mute interval</emphasis>
: Syllable: 64 ± 10 ms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF12FDDFFD94FD3C" blockId="43.[151,545,618,644]" box="[151,545,618,644]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FF12FDDFFD94FD3C" bold="true" box="[151,545,618,644]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">3.9. Scaphurae Westwood, 1838</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D7B0C6BFF83EF40FF12FD07FBDFFCAC" blockId="43.[151,1437,690,789]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
This group presents only the genus 
<taxonomicName id="9AC477E8FF83EF40FDB7FD07FD28FD74" box="[562,669,690,716]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Scaphura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6FB0D079FF83EF40FDB7FD07FD28FD74" box="[562,669,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Scaphura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with 11 species, restricted to the South American continent (Neotropical Region, Andean Region and South American Transition Zone). Seven species are currently recognized for 
<collectingCountry id="25D34CFBFF83EF40FF12FD4FFF6BFCAC" box="[151,222,762,788]" name="Brazil" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and here we recorded three species, including a possible new species to science.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
